1/* Copyright 1990-2017 The MathWorks, Inc. */



2/*



3 * File: simstruc.h



4 *



5 * Abstract:



6 *      Data structures and access methods for S-functions.



7 *



8 *      A Simulink model is an S-function.  The SimStruct contains all entry



9 *      points within the S-function (e.g. mdlOutputs) as well any data



10 *      associated with the S-function.



11 *



12 *      This file contains details of SimStruct (Simulink data structure)



13 *      which is used to store attributes of the model such as pointers to



14 *      storage vectors.



15 *



16 *      Multiple SimStructs are, in general, used by a model. These SimStruct's



17 *      are arranged as a "tree". The "root" SimStruct is used by



18 *      the Simulink model. There is one child SimStruct for each S-function



19 *      block with in the model.



20 *



21 *      The SimStruct can be used in three environments:



22 *        o With MATLAB/Simulink (MATLAB_MEX_FILE)



23 *        o With Real-Time Workshop in non-real-time (NRT)



24 *        o With Real-Time Workshop in real-time (RT)



25 *



26 * Defines:



27 *      One of the following must be defined.



28 *        MATLAB_MEX_FILE    - Must be defined when compiling as a MEX file,



29 *                             otherwise must not be defined.



30 *        NRT                - Define if creating non-real-time executable



31 *        RT                 - Define if creating real-time executable.



32 *



33 *        See ENVIRONMENT MACROS section below for more info.



34 *



35 *      Defines which must be declared by the Real-Time Workshop



36 *      generated model source.



37 *        Simulink_NAME="name"



38 *        NSAMPLE_TIMES=n



39 *



40 *      Defines for use with the Real-Time Workshop (these are configured



41 *	by the template makefile, do not add directly to make command):



42 *        MULTITASKING       - Optional (use MT for a synonym).



43 *        NUMST=n            - Number of sample times in the root SimStruct.



44 *        TID01EQ=1 or 0     - Optional. Only define to 1 if sample time task



45 *                             id's 0 and 1 have equal rates.



46 * =============================================================================



47 */



48



49#ifdef __clang__



50#pragma clang diagnostic push

53#pragma clang diagnostic ignored "-Wreserved-id-macro"

55#endif



56#endif

61/*===========================================================================*



62 * BEGIN SECTION



63 * LIST OF KEY DEFINES CONTROLLING CONDITIONAL COMPILATION



64 *



65 * Simstruc properties such as definitions, access methods, etc.



66 * are conditionally compiled depending on "who" is using the simstruc



67 * and in what mode.



68 *



69 * This section list all the key #define macros controlling the inclusion/



70 * exclusion of features, definitions, etc.



71 *



72 * Typically, this section only assigns a default value (such as false).



73 * The final value is adjusted in a subsequent section.



74 *===========================================================================*/



75



76/*=======================================================*



77 * MODE: SINGLE-TASKING OR MULTI-TASKING



78 */



79#define SS_MULTITASKING (0)



80



81/*=======================================================*



82 * MODE: SIMULATION OR GENERATED CODE



83 *



84 * The following #defines determine whether the simstruc is used in "normal"



85 * Simulink simulation or in Real Time Workshop generated code.



86 *



87 * This is designed to be a mutually exclusive set.



88 * One and only one should be defined to be true.



89 */



90#define SS_SIM (0)



91#define SS_RTW (0)



92



93/*=======================================================*



94 * MODE: WHO IS USING THE SIMSTRUC



95 *



96 * The following #defines determine "who" is using the simstruc.



97 *



98 * This is designed to be a mutually exclusive set.



99 * One and only one should be defined to be true.



100 */



101#define SS_SFCN_LEVEL_1         (0)



102#define SS_SFCN_NORMAL          (0)



103#define SS_GENERATED_S_FUNCTION (0)



104#define SS_SL_INTERNAL          (0)



105#define SS_RTW_INTERNAL         (0)



106#define SS_SHARED_MODULE        (0)



107



108/*=======================================================*



109 * MODE: GENERATED CODE IS REAL-TIME OR NON-REAL-TIME



110 *



111 * Both can be false, but both can't be true



112 */



113#define SS_RT  (0)



114#define SS_NRT (0)



115



116/*=======================================================*



117 * MODE: ENFORCE NDEBUG



118 */



119#define SS_NDEBUG (0)



120



121/*=======================================================*



122 * MODE: ENVIRONMENT HAS STANDARD IO AVAILABLE



123 */



124#define SS_HAVESTDIO (0)



125



126/*=======================================================*



127 * MODE: TID_EQUALS_SAMPLE_TIME_INDEX -



128 *     The model will function correctly if this define is false, however if



129 *     this define is true the model's performance may be increased depending



130 *     upon whether or not the model has fast to slow rate transitions.



131 */



132#define TID_EQUALS_SAMPLE_TIME_INDEX (0)



133



134/*=======================================================*



135 * MODE: TID01EQ == 1



136 */



137#define SS_TID01EQ_EQUAL_ONE (0)



138

140 * END SECTION

142 *===========================================================================*/

217#if defined(RTW_GENERATED_S_FUNCTION)



218  /*



219   * Used by RTW Generated S Function, ex  s-fcn target.



220   * This flag is independent of how the



221   * s-function is built (i.e., it is a #define in the code, not a build



222   * flag).  It is true when building the s-function for use with simulink and



223   * when building the s-function for use with RTW.



224   */



225# undef  SS_GENERATED_S_FUNCTION



226# define SS_GENERATED_S_FUNCTION (1)



227



228#elif S_FUNCTION_LEVEL == 1



229  /*



230   * Used with any LEVEL 1 s-function (user written) including:



231   *  o build for use with a normal simulation (via mex command)



232   *  o build for use with rtw (grt)



233   */



234# undef  SS_SFCN_LEVEL_1



235# define SS_SFCN_LEVEL_1   (1)

237#elif defined(S_FUNCTION_NAME)

241   *  o build for use with rtw (grt)

246#elif defined(SL_INTERNAL) || defined(RSIM_WITH_SL_SOLVER)



247  /*



248   * Used internally by Simulink (simulink.dll).



249   */



250# undef  SS_SL_INTERNAL



251# define SS_SL_INTERNAL    (1)



252



253#elif defined(RT) || defined(NRT)



254  /*



255   * Used in "root" model of generated code, but not in



256   * non-inlined, s-functions being compiled for use with the



257   * generated code (i.e., rt_main and model.c have access, but



258   * sfunc.c does not).



259   */



260# undef  SS_RTW_INTERNAL



261# define SS_RTW_INTERNAL   (1)



262



263#elif defined(FIPXT_SHARED_MODULE)



264  /*



265   * Used in shared module (such as a dll) that needs to be able to



266   * use some feature of the simstruc.



267   */



268/*



269 * Currently, shared module will be treated as if they are



270 * normal sfunctions.



271 *



272# undef  SS_SHARED_MODULE



273# define SS_SHARED_MODULE  (1)



274*/



275# undef  SS_SFCN_NORMAL



276# define SS_SFCN_NORMAL    (1)



277



278#elif defined(MATLAB_MEX_FILE)



279  /*  Used in mex function that is NOT an S-Function mex



280   */



281/*



282 * Currently, plain mex functions will be treated as if they are



283 * normal sfunctions.



284 *



285# undef  SS_MEX



286# define SS_MEX  (1)

288# undef  SS_SFCN_NORMAL



289# define SS_SFCN_NORMAL    (1)

501/*===========================================================================*



502 *===========================================================================*



503 *===========================================================================*



504 * WARNING: For maintainability:



505 *



506 * Conditional Compilation below this point should only depend on



507 *    KEY DEFINES



508 * or



509 *    GROUP DEFINES



510 * that where determined in the sections above.



511 *



512 * In particular, #if and #elif should only depend on the KEY DEFINES and/or



513 * GROUP DEFINES.



514 *



515 * All the KEY DEFINES and GROUP DEFINES always have definitions.  Therefore,



516 * the preprocessor directives defined(), #ifdef, and #ifndef are not needed



517 * below, and their use indicates a likely maintainability problem.  The



518 * only exception is the use of #ifndef in the standard technique for guarding



519 * against multiple inclusion and multiple definition.



520 *===========================================================================*

529/*



530 * DYNAMICALLY_SIZED - Specify for sizes entries that inherit their values



531 * from the block that drives them.



532 * SIMSTRUCT_VERSION - An integer which is the sizeof the SimStruct times



533 * 10000 plus the version times 100. When updating version numbers within the



534 * Matlab image, increment both level 1 and level 2 S-functions. Level 1



535 * version cannot be in range 220 to 229.  This was the level 2 version in



536 * Simulink 2.20 (R10)



537 *



538 * DYNAMIC_DIMENSION - Specify for input/output port dimension entries that



539 * the port inherits its dimension from the block that drives it.



540 */



541



542#define ALWAYS_NEEDED          (0)



543#define CONDITIONALLY_NEEDED   (1)



544#define NEVER_NEEDED           (2)



545



546#define ALWAYS_REFRESHED          (0)



547#define CONDITIONALLY_REFRESHED   (1)



548#define NEVER_REFRESHED           (2)



549



550#define SIMSTRUCT_VERSION_LEVEL1     (sizeof(SimStruct)*10000 + 214)



551#define SIMSTRUCT_VERSION_LEVEL2     (sizeof(SimStruct)*10000 + 229)

563#define ssSampleAndOffsetAreTriggered(st,ot) \



564((st == INHERITED_SAMPLE_TIME) && (ot == INHERITED_SAMPLE_TIME))



565#define ssSampleAndOffsetAreTriggeredOrAsync(st,ot) \



566((st == INHERITED_SAMPLE_TIME) && (ot <= INHERITED_SAMPLE_TIME))



567



568/*



569 * Task ID's ordering



570 *      Continuous task



571 *      Continuous but fixed in minor step task



572 *      Discrete task 1



573 *         ...



574 *      Discrete task N



575 *      Variable sample time task(s), offset is instance number.



576 *



577 * If continuous task is present then it's task ID is 0, otherwise the



578 * first discrete task ID will be 0 if it is present, etc.



579 * All blocks with varying sample times have same sample task period of -2,



580 * and the offset is the instance number.



581 *



582 * The triggered blocks are not in the sample time table and have a task ID



583 * of -1.



584 */



585



586#define CONSTANT_TID            (-2)



587#define GENERIC_ASYNC_TID       (-3)



588#define COMPOSITE_TID           (-4)



589#define PARAMETER_TUNING_TID    (-5)



590

592 * PropagationPassType - used to distinguish for pass initialization



593 * If you add or update PropagationPassType, update simulink/sl_types_compile.hpp too



594 *==========================================================================*/



595#ifndef _PROPAGATIONPASSTYPE



596# define _PROPAGATIONPASSTYPE

598        DIMENSION_PROPAGATION,



599        TYPE_PROPAGATION,



600        COMPLEX_PROPAGATION,



601        UNIT_PROPAGATION



602    } PropagationPassType;



603#endif

610/*===============================================*

615/*



616 * Conversion routines for frame data storage



617 */



618#define NEG1_2BITS '\x03'



619#define CONV_BITS2INT(val) \



620          ( (((val) & 2U) != 0U) ? FRAME_INHERITED : (((val) & 1U) != 0U) ? FRAME_YES : FRAME_NO )



621#define CONV_INT2BITS(val) \



622          ( ((val) == FRAME_INHERITED) ? (NEG1_2BITS) : ((val) & 1U) )



623



624/*



625 * Conversion routines for dimensions mode storage



626 */



627#define CONV_BITS2DIMSMODE(val) \



628          ( (((val) & 2U) != 0) ? INHERIT_DIMS_MODE : (((val) & 1U) != 0U) ? VARIABLE_DIMS_MODE : FIXED_DIMS_MODE )



629#define CONV_DIMSMODE2BITS(val) \



630          ( ((val) == INHERIT_DIMS_MODE) ? (NEG1_2BITS) : ((val) & 1U) )



631



632/*



633 * Conversion routines for bus mode storage



634 */



635#define CONV_BITS2BUSMODE(val) \



636          ( (((val) & 2U) != 0) ? SL_INHERIT_BUS_MODE : (((val) & 1U) != 0U) ? SL_BUS_MODE : SL_NON_BUS_MODE )



637#define CONV_BUSMODE2BITS(val) \



638          ( ((val) == SL_INHERIT_BUS_MODE) ? (NEG1_2BITS) : ((val) & 1U) )

698/*=================================================================*



699 * Defines for use by External Mode during simulation              *



700 *=================================================================*/



701#ifndef ExtModeLogBlockMeth_def



702#define ExtModeLogBlockMeth_def



703typedef enum {



704    /*



705     * Called when the user request the trigger to be armed (i.e., after



706     * the 'arm trigger' button is pressed and the trigger arm message



707     * has successfully been handed off to ext_comm).



708     */



709    EXTLOGTASK_TRIG_ARM,



710



711    /*



712     * Called when the first point of a one-shot arrives.



713     */



714    EXTLOGTASK_INIT_EVENT,



715



716    /*



717     * Definitions:



718     *  one-shot:    one buffer of data collected when the trigger fires.



719     *  normal-mode: a series of one-shots



720     *



721     * When in normal mode, each buffer in the series, except for the last



722     * buffer is consider to be an 'intermediate' buffer.  When the final



723     * point of an intermediate buffer has arrived on the host, the



724     * EXTLOGTASK_TERM_INTERMEDIATE_ONESHOT method is called.  When the



725     * final point of the last buffer of the series arrives, the



726     * EXTLOGTASK_TERM_SESSION is called.



727     *



728     * Note that when not in normal mode, the



729     * EXTLOGTASK_TERM_INTERMEDIATE_ONESHOT method is never called.



730     *



731     * Also see EXTLOGTASK_TERM_SESSION.



732     */



733    EXTLOGTASK_TERM_INTERMEDIATE_ONESHOT,



734



735    /*



736     * Called when:



737     *  o In normal mode and the last point of the last buffer in a one-shot



738     *    series has arrived (i.e., this is the end of the current log session).



739     *



740     *  o When in one-shot mode and the final point arrives (again this is the



741     *    end of the logging session since the one and only buffer has been



742     *    acquired).



743     *



744     *  See comments for: EXTLOGTASK_TERM_INTERMEDIATE_ONESHOT



745     */



746    EXTLOGTASK_TERM_SESSION



747



748} ExtModeLogBlockMeth;



749#endif

873      unsigned int isConcurrentTasks        :1;



874

876      unsigned int crlReplacementEnabled :1;

879      



880      /* each bit field has to be no more than 16 bits!  (some targets, for ex,



881         TI 2000, do not support more than 16 bits per single field */

885



886  void       *rtModel;       /* rtModel pointer */



887  const void *constBlockIO;  /* Pointer to invariant signals */



888



889  /*



890   * The funky statements below were necessitated because we originally



891   * had 5 reserved integer fields. In order to get a (void *) field



892   * we need one int on certain platforms and two on others. To



893   * overcome this, we have the definition below.



894   *



895   * Note that there is only ONE remaining reserved int (for alpha



896   * anyway, there are 3 on other platforms i.e. the ones where



897   * sizeof(int) = sizeof(void*) )



898   *



899   * In order to use it, there will need to be added some appropriate



900   * pre-processor definitions to keep from attempting to instantiate



901   * an array of length 0.



902   *



903   * The problem is that on alpha sizeof(void *) = 64 and



904   * sizeof(int) = 32 so we have:



905   *   4 - 2*sizeof(void *)/sizeof(int) = 4 - 2*64/32 = 0



906   */



907  int  reservedForFuture[5 - 2*sizeof(void *)/sizeof(int)];



908};

1648#if SS_SL_INTERNAL || SS_SFCN_FOR_SIM



1649  /*



1650   * The following return error string on failure, NULL on success.



1651   * See <matlabroot>/simulink/src/barplot.c for an example of using



1652   * these functions.



1653   */



1654



1655  /*



1656   * Returns an array of output port pointers corresponding to the selected



1657   * signals in the window that the s-function block resides (i.e., the signals



1658   * whose lines have selection handles).  There are two options that can



1659   * be passed to this function (sigSetOpt):



1660   *    SIGSET_GRAPH: return only the selected signals in the window in



1661   *                  which the s-function resides.



1662   *    SIGSET_GRAPH_N_CHILDREN: return selected signals in the window in



1663   *                             which the s-function resides and all



1664   *                             children windows.

1771/*

1773 * SimStruct's point to the root SimStruct mdlInfo field.  Care must be taken

1775 * (e.g. t, sample hits, sample times, etc). from child SimStruct's (use macros



1776 * below).

1831                                             * size is less than the min step

2075



2076/*



2077 * Level 2 S-function methods:



2078 *



2079 * [mdlInitializePropagationPassFcn] - Optional routine. Perform any



2080 *                                 necessary initialization before the



2081 *                                 specified propagation pass begins.



2082 *=> mdlInitializeSizes         -  Initialize SimStruct sizes array



2083 *   [mdlSetInputPortWidth]     -  Optional routine. Check and set input and



2084 *                                 optionally other port widths.  Can



2085 *                                 only be in a C MEX S-function.



2086 *   [mdlSetOutputPortWidth]    -  Optional routine. Check and set output



2087 *                                 and optionally other port widths. Can



2088 *                                 only be in a C MEX S-function.



2089 *   [mdlSetInputPortFrameData] -  Optional routine. Check and set input and



2090 *                                 optionally other frame data.  Can



2091 *                                 only be in a C MEX S-function.



2092 *=> mdlInitializeSampleTimes   -  Initialize sample times.



2093 *   [mdlSetWorkWidths]         -  Optional routine. Set the state, iwork,



2094 *                                 rwork, pwork, etc sizes. Can only be in a



2095 *                                 C MEX S-function.



2096 *



2097 *   [mdlRTW]                   -  Optional routine.  Only called when



2098 *                                 generating code to add information to the



2099 *                                 model.rtw file which is used by the



2100 *                                 Real-Time Workshop.



2101 *



2102 *   <<End mdl function calls when generating code by the Real-Time Workshop>>



2103 *



2104 *   [mdlInitializeConditions]  -  Initialize model parameters (usually



2105 *                                 states). Will not be called if your



2106 *                                 S-function does not have an initialize



2107 *                                 conditions routine.



2108 *   [mdlStart]                 -  Optional routine. Perform actions such



2109 *                                 as allocating memory and attaching to pwork



2110 *                                 elements.  Can only be in a C MEX



2111 *                                 S-function.



2112 *   [mdlCheckParameters]       -  Optional routine. Will be called at



2113 *                                 any time during the simulation loop when



2114 *                                 parameters change. Can only be used in a



2115 *                                 C MEX S-function.



2116 *   [mdlExtModeExec]           -  Optional routine. Will be called during



2117 *                                 external mode simulation loop to run the



2118 *                                 C Mex S-function block.



2119 *   SimulationLoop:



2120 *        [mdlProcessParameters]   -  Optional routine. Called during



2121 *                                    simulation after parameters have been



2122 *                                    changed and verified to be okay by



2123 *                                    mdlCheckParameters. The processing is



2124 *                                    done at the "top" of the simulation loop



2125 *                                    when it is safe to process the changed



2126 *                                    parameters. Can only be used in a C MEX



2127 *                                    S-function.



2128 *        [mdlGetTimeOfNextVarHit] -  Optional routine. If your S-function



2129 *                                    has a variable step sample time, then



2130 *                                    this routine will be called.



2131 *        [mdlInitializeConditions] -  Optional routine. Only called if your



2132 *                                    S-function resides in an enabled



2133 *                                    subsystem configured to reset states,



2134 *                                    and the subsystem has just enabled.



2135 *     => mdlOutputs               -  Major output call (usually updates



2136 *                                    output signals).



2137 *        [mdlUpdate]              -  Update the discrete states, etc.



2138 *        [mdlDerivatives]         -  Compute the derivatives.



2139 *   EndLoop



2140 *   mdlTerminate               -  End of model housekeeping - free memory,



2141 *                                 etc.



2142 */



2143

2500struct SimStruct_tag {



2501



2502  const char_T           *modelName;  /* Name of the Simulink model/Sfunc    */



2503



2504  const char_T           *path;       /* Full "Simulink path" to this s-fcn  */



2505



2506  SimStruct              *parent;     /* Parent SimStruct                    */



2507  SimStruct              *root;       /* Root level SimStruct                */



2508



2509  union {



2510	const char_T* str;                  /* Execution status. Setting to non-NULL



2511                                         during any mdlFunction will stop the



2512                                         simulation and the "status" message



2513                                         will be displayed.                  */



2514	void*  msg;



2515  } errorStatus;



2516



2517  struct _ssSizes        sizes;        /* Sizes (returned when flag==0)      */



2518



2519  struct _ssPortInfo     portInfo;    /* Input and output port properties



2520                                         such as width and direct feedthrough



2521                                         setting.                            */



2522



2523  struct _ssSFcnParams   sfcnParams;  /* S-function parameters passed in



2524                                         P1,...,Pn                           */



2525



2526  struct _ssStates       states;      /* Input, output, state, derivative,



2527                                         etc. vectors                        */



2528



2529  struct _ssWork         work;        /* Various work areas (rwork, iwork,



2530                                         pwork, user data, block I/O,



2531                                         block params, etc.)                 */



2532



2533  struct _ssBlkInfo      blkInfo;     /* Information about S-function blocks */



2534



2535  struct _ssMdlInfo      *mdlInfo;    /* Model-wide info. All children



2536                                         SimStruct point to root mdlInfo     */



2537



2538  struct _ssCallSys      callSys;     /* For use when S-function calls a



2539                                         "function-call" subsystems          */



2540



2541  struct _ssRegDataType  regDataType; /* For Registering Data type           */



2542



2543  struct _ssStInfo       stInfo;      /* Sample time, offset time, etc.      */



2544



2545  struct {



2546      struct _ssSFcnModelMethods sFcn; /* For S-functions                    */



2547  } modelMethods;



2548



2549  struct SimStruct_tag   **sFunctions;/* SimStruct's for S-Functions



2550                                         referenced via S-Function blocks.



2551                                         Used only with RT and NRT.          */



2552};

2556/*======================================*



2557 * SimStruct Get and Set Access methods *



2558 *======================================*/



2559



2560/*-------------------------------- S->modelName -----------------------------*/



2561



2562/*



2563 * ModelName - This is the name of the S-function. When the SimStruct



2564 *   is being used with the Real-Time Workshop, then the "root" SimStruct



2565 *   model name corresponds to the name of the Simulink model.



2566 */



2567#define ssGetModelName(S) \



2568          (S)->modelName                                  /* (const char_T*) */



2569#define _ssSetModelName(S, name) \



2570          (S)->modelName = (name)



2571#if !SS_SFCN



2572#define ssSetModelName(S,name) _ssSetModelName(S,name)



2573#else



2574#define ssSetModelName(S,name) ssSetModelName_cannot_be_used_in_SFunctions



2575#endif



2576



2577/*-------------------------------- S->path ----------------------------------*/



2578/*



2579 * Path - This is the full path to the S-function. When the SimStruct



2580 *   is being used with the Real-Time Workshop, then the "root" SimStruct



2581 *   path corresponds to the name of the Simulink model.



2582 */



2583#define ssGetPath(S) \



2584          (S)->path                                       /* (const char_T*) */



2585#define _ssSetPath(S, pathPtr) \



2586          (S)->path = (pathPtr)



2587#if !SS_SFCN



2588#define ssSetPath(S,pathPtr) _ssSetPath(S,pathPtr)



2589#else



2590#define ssSetPath(S,pathPtr) ssSetPath_cannot_be_used_in_SFunctions



2591#endif



2592



2593/*-------------------------------- S->parent --------------------------------*/



2594/*



2595 * ParentSS - There is one SimStruct for each S-function in your model.



2596 *   There is also a SimStruct for the model itself. The SimStruct's are



2597 *   arranged as a tree with the model SimStruct as the root. The ParentSS



2598 *   field is used to get at the model SimStruct. User written S-functions



2599 *   should not use the ssGetParentSS macro directly.



2600 */



2601#define ssGetParentSS(S) \



2602          (S)->parent                                     /*   (SimStruct *) */



2603#define _ssSetParentSS(S,parentSS) \



2604          (S)->parent = (parentSS)



2605#if !SS_SFCN



2606#define ssSetParentSS(S,parentSS) _ssSetParentSS(S,parentSS)



2607#else



2608#define ssSetParentSS(S,parentSS) ssSetParentSS_cannot_be_used_in_SFunctions



2609#endif



2610



2611/*-------------------------------- S->root ----------------------------------*/



2612/*



2613 * RootSS - This is the "root" SimStruct corresponding to the Simulink



2614 *   model.



2615 */



2616#define ssGetRootSS(S) \



2617          (S)->root                                       /*   (SimStruct *) */



2618#define _ssSetRootSS(S,rootSS) \



2619          (S)->root = (rootSS)



2620#if !SS_SFCN



2621#define ssSetRootSS(S,rootSS) _ssSetRootSS(S,rootSS)



2622#else



2623#define ssSetRootSS(S,rootSS) ssSetRootSS_cannot_be_used_in_SFunctions



2624#endif



2625



2626



2627/*-------------------------------- S->errorStatus ---------------------------*/



2628



2629/* ErrorStatus - For improved performance and error handling, your S-function



2630 *   should do:



2631 *      ssSetErrorStatus(S, "error message");



2632 *      return;



2633 *   as opposed to calling mexErrMsgTxt.



2634 *



2635 *   Be careful when using ssSetErrorStatus in your S-function. Sometimes you



2636 *   may wish to use sprintf to format the message. In this case, you



2637 *   need to allocate memory for the message as opposed to using the stack.



2638 *   macros _ss[SG]et_slErrMsg and _ssIsErrorStatusAslErrMsg



2639 *   are intended for internal use only



2640 */



2641



2642#define ssGetErrorStatus(S) \



2643          ssGetRootSS(S)->errorStatus.str                  /* (const char_T*) */



2644#define ssSetErrorStatus(S, string) \



2645       { ssGetRootSS(S)->mdlInfo->mdlFlags.errorStatusIsMsg = 0U; \



2646        ssGetRootSS(S)->errorStatus.str = (string); }



2647



2648#define _ssGetErrorStatus(S) \



2649       ( ssGetRootSS(S)->mdlInfo->mdlFlags.errorStatusIsMsg == 1U ? \



2650       NULL : ssGetRootSS(S)->errorStatus.str )



2651#define _ssGet_slErrMsg(S) \



2652       ( ssGetRootSS(S)->mdlInfo->mdlFlags.errorStatusIsMsg == 0U ? \



2653       NULL : ssGetRootSS(S)->errorStatus.msg )



2654#define _ssSet_slErrMsg(S, msg_arg) \



2655        { ssGetRootSS(S)->mdlInfo->mdlFlags.errorStatusIsMsg = 1U; \



2656        ssGetRootSS(S)->errorStatus.msg = (msg_arg); }



2657#define _ssIsErrorStatusAslErrMsg(S) \



2658        ( ssGetRootSS(S)->mdlInfo->mdlFlags.errorStatusIsMsg == 1U )



2659



2660#define _ssReportDiagnosticAsWarning(S, diag)                                  \



2661    _ssSafelyCallGenericFcnStart(S)((S), GEN_FCN_REPORT_DIAGNOSTIC_AS_WARNING, \



2662                                    0, diag) _ssSafelyCallGenericFcnEnd



2663



2664#define SS_ERROR_STATUS_BUFFER_SIZE 1024



2665



2666#define _ssCopyErrorStatusToBuffer(S, string, size) \



2667      { (void)memcpy(ssGetRootSS(S)->mdlInfo->errorStatusBuffer, (string), ((size) > SS_ERROR_STATUS_BUFFER_SIZE-1)? (SS_ERROR_STATUS_BUFFER_SIZE-1) : (size) ); \



2668      ssSetErrorStatus(S, ssGetRootSS(S)->mdlInfo->errorStatusBuffer); }



2669/*-------------------------------- S->sizes ---------------------------------*/

2673 *   (above).



2674 */



2675#define ssGetSizesPtr(S) \



2676          ((int_T *)&(S)->sizes)                          /*   (int_T *)     */

2678/* NumContStates - This is the number of continuous states within your



2679 *   S-function. The root SimStruct contains the number of continuous states



2680 *   within the model itself (including all blocks and S-functions).

2690 */

2700 */

3302/*************************



3303 * Input Port Dimensions *



3304 *************************/



3305/*  ssGetInputPortDimensionSize returns the size of a specified



3306 *  dimension at the input port. If the dimension index is greater



3307 *  than or equal to the number of input port dimensions,



3308 *  ssGetInputPortDimensionSize returns 1.



3309 */

3494 /* InputPortSignalPtrs - This is the pointers to the signal vector for each



3495  *    input port. This is the default method for accessing the S-Function's



3496  *    input signals. It is a *bad* error to use this macro if the S-Function



3497  *    specifies ssSetInputPortRequiredContiguous as true. In that case, use



3498  *    ssGetInputPortSignal().



3499  *



3500  *    The following code demonstrates the use of ssGetInputPortSignalPtrs() :



3501  *



3502  *       nInputPorts = ssGetNumInputPorts(S);



3503  *       for (i = 0; i < nInputPorts; i++) {



3504  *         InputPtrsType u  = ssGetInputPortSignalPtrs(S,i);



3505  *         int_T         nu = ssGetInputPortWidth(S,i);



3506  *         for (j = 0; j < nu; j++) {



3507  *           UseInputInSomeFunction(*u[i]);



3508  *         }



3509  *       }



3510  *



3511  *    If you know that the input's are always real_T's signals, then the



3512  *    ssGetInputPortSignalPtrs line in the above code snippet would be:



3513  *



3514  *         InputRealPtrsType u = ssGetInputPortRealSignalPtrs(S,i);



3515  *



3516  */



3517# if SS_SFCN_FOR_SIM && !SS_NDEBUG



3518#  ifdef __cplusplus



3519    extern "C" {



3520#  endif



3521    extern InputPtrsType _ssGetInputPortSignalPtrsFcn(const SimStruct *S,



3522                                                      int ip);



3523#  ifdef __cplusplus



3524    }



3525#  endif



3526#   define ssGetInputPortSignalPtrs(S,ip) _ssGetInputPortSignalPtrsFcn(S,ip)



3527#   define ssGetInputPortRealSignalPtrs(S,ip) \



3528        ((InputRealPtrsType)_ssGetInputPortSignalPtrsFcn(S,ip))



3529# else



3530#  define ssGetInputPortSignalPtrs(S,ip) \



3531     ( (S)->portInfo.inputs[(ip)].signal.ptrs )      /* (InputPtrsType) */



3532#  define ssGetInputPortRealSignalPtrs(S,ip) \



3533     ( (InputRealPtrsType) ssGetInputPortSignalPtrs(S,ip) )



3534# endif



3535



3536# define _ssSetInputPortSignalPtrs(S,ip,ptr) \



3537    (S)->portInfo.inputs[(ip)].signal.ptrs = (ptr)



3538# if !SS_SFCN



3539#   define ssSetInputPortSignalPtrs(S,ip,ptr) \



3540      _ssSetInputPortSignalPtrs(S,ip,ptr)



3541# else

3543      ssSetInputPortSignalPtrs_cannot_be_used_in_SFunctions

3547 /* InputPortSignal: This macro returns the address of the signal on the



3548  *    specified input port of the S-Function. In order to use this macro for



3549  *    accessing the input port signal you need to set the attribute



3550  *    ssSetInputPortRequiredContiguous to true. If not, this macro returns an



3551  *    invalid pointer.



3552  *



3553  *    The following code demonstrates the use of ssGetInputPortSignal() :



3554  *



3555  *       nInputPorts = ssGetNumInputPorts(S);



3556  *       for (i = 0; i < nInputPorts; i++) {



3557  *           int_T nu = ssGetInputPortWidth(S,i);



3558  *



3559  *           if ( ssGetInputPortRequiredContiguous(S,i) ) {



3560  *



3561  *               const void *u = ssGetInputPortSignal(S,i);



3562  *               UseInputVectorInSomeFunction(u, nu);



3563  *



3564  *           } else {



3565  *



3566  *               InputPtrsType u  = ssGetInputPortSignalPtrs(S,i);



3567  *               for (j = 0; j < nu; j++) {



3568  *                   UseInputInSomeFunction(*u[j]);



3569  *               }



3570  *           }



3571  *       }



3572  *



3573  *    If you know that the input's are always real_T's signals, then the



3574  *    ssGetInputPortSignal line in the above code snippet would be:



3575  *



3576  *         const real_T *u = ssGetInputPortRealSignal(S,i);



3577  *



3578  */



3579# if SS_SFCN_FOR_SIM && !SS_NDEBUG



3580#  ifdef __cplusplus



3581    extern "C" {



3582#  endif



3583    extern const void *_ssGetInputPortSignalFcn(const SimStruct *S, int ip);



3584#  ifdef __cplusplus



3585   }



3586#  endif



3587#   define ssGetInputPortSignal(S,ip) _ssGetInputPortSignalFcn(S,ip)



3588#   define ssGetInputPortRealSignal(S,ip) \



3589        ((const real_T *)_ssGetInputPortSignalFcn(S,ip))



3590# else



3591#  define ssGetInputPortSignal(S,ip) \



3592     ( (S)->portInfo.inputs[(ip)].signal.vect )       /* (const void *) */



3593#  define ssGetInputPortRealSignal(S,ip) \



3594     ( (const real_T *) ssGetInputPortSignal(S,ip) )



3595# endif



3596



3597# define _ssSetInputPortSignal(S,ip,ptr) \



3598          (S)->portInfo.inputs[(ip)].signal.vect = (ptr)

3699/* InputPortOptimizeInIR - This macro allows S-Functions that use the code

3762 /* InputPortRequiredContiguous - If this flag is set to true (the default



3763  *   value is false), then the S-Function input signal's starting address



3764  *   should be accessed via ssGetInputPortSignal(), and then you can "walk"



3765  *   this pointer from 0 to portWidth-1 to read the values of the input



3766  *   signal elements. The S-Function can set the value of this attribute



3767  *   as early as in mdlInitializeSizes() method and at the latest in



3768  *   mdlSetWorkWidths() method. If this attribute is set any later than the



3769  *   mdlSetWorkWidths() method, say in mdlStart() or mdlOutputs(), horrible



3770  *   things will happen.



3771  *



3772  * Notes:



3773  *   As mentioned above, the default setting for this flag is false,



3774  *   hence, the default method of accessing the input signals of a



3775  *   Level-2 S-Function is using ssGetInputSignalPtrs().



3776  */



3777# define ssGetInputPortRequiredContiguous(S,port) \



3778   ((S)->portInfo.inputs[(port)].attributes.contiguity != 0)



3779# define ssSetInputPortRequiredContiguous(S,port,val) \



3780   (S)->portInfo.inputs[(port)].attributes.contiguity = ((val)!=0)

3827 * dimension at the output port. If the dimension index is greater

3845}

3847/*

3849 * port has enough storage/memory to store the dimensions.

3851# define _ssCopyOutputPortDimensions(S,port,d) \



3852{\

3854    if(nn >= 1){\

4233



4234/*



4235 * Set any S-function options which must be OR'd together.



4236 * For example:  ssSetOptions(S, SS_OPTION_EXCEPTION_FREE_CODE |



4237 *                              SS_OPTION_DISCRETE_VALUED_OUTPUT);



4238 *



4239 * The available options are:



4240 * SS_OPTION_EXCEPTION_FREE_CODE - if your S-function does not use



4241 *   mexErrMsgTxt, mxCalloc, or any other routines which can throw an



4242 *   exception when called, you can set this option for improved



4243 *   performance.



4244 *



4245 * SS_OPTION_RUNTIME_EXCEPTION_FREE_CODE - Similar to



4246 *   SS_OPTION_EXCEPTION_FREE_CODE except it only applies to the "run-time"



4247 *   routines: mdlGetTimeOfNextVarHit, mdlOutputs, mdlUpdate, and



4248 *   mdlDerivatives.



4249 *



4250 * SS_OPTION_DISCRETE_VALUED_OUTPUT - This should be specified if your



4251 *   S-function has a discrete valued outputs.  This is checked when



4252 *   your S-function is placed within an algebraic loop. If your S-function



4253 *   has discrete valued outputs, then its outputs will not be assigned



4254 *   algebraic variables.



4255 *



4256 * SS_OPTION_PLACE_ASAP - This is used to specify that your S-function



4257 *   should be placed as soon as possible. This is typically used by



4258 *   devices connecting to hardware.



4259 *



4260 * SS_OPTION_ALLOW_INPUT_SCALAR_EXPANSION - This is used to specify



4261 *   that the input to your S-function input ports can be either 1 or



4262 *   the size specified by the port which is usually referred to as



4263 *   the block width.



4264 *



4265 * SS_OPTION_DISALLOW_CONSTANT_SAMPLE_TIME - This is used to disable



4266 *   your S-function block from inheriting a constant sample time.



4267 *



4268 * SS_OPTION_ASYNCHRONOUS - This option applies only to S-functions that



4269 *   have no input ports during code generation and 1 output port.



4270 *   During simulation, the S-function may have an input port to provide



4271 *   a condition on which to execute. The output port must be configured to



4272 *   perform function calls on every element.  If any of these requirements



4273 *   are not met, the SS_OPTION_ASYNCHRONOUS is ignored.  Use this option



4274 *   when driving function-call subsystems that will be attached to



4275 *   asynchronous tasks. Specifying this



4276 *     1) Informs Simulink that there is no implied data dependency involving



4277 *        the data sources or destinations of the function-call subsystem called



4278 *        by the S-function.



4279 *     2) Causes the function-call subsystem attached to the S-function to be



4280 *        colored cyan indicating that it does not execute at a periodic rate.



4281 *     3) Enables additional checks to verify that the model is



4282 *        constructed correctly:



4283 *          a) Simulink validates that the appropriate asynchronous rate



4284 *             transition blocks reside between the (cyan) function-call



4285 *             subsystem and period tasks exists. You can always directly



4286 *             read & write from the function-call subsys by using a block



4287 *             similar to the 'vxlib/Asynchronous Support/Rate Transition'



4288 *             block that has no computational overhead (look at the Tag value



4289 *             on the Outport block within the Rate Transition masked



4290 *             subsystem). Safe task transitions between period and



4291 *             asynchronous tasks are created by using the



4292 *             SS_OPTION_ASYNC_RATE_TRANSITION.



4293 *             See the 'vxlib/Asynchronous Support' library.



4294 *          b) For data transfers between two asynchronously executed (cycan)



4295 *             function-call subsystem, Simulink validates that the appropriate



4296 *             asynchronous task transition blocks exits.



4297 *             See the 'vxlib/Asynchronous Support' library.



4298 *



4299 * SS_OPTION_ASYNCHRONOUS_INTERRUPT - This option is very similar to



4300 *   SS_OPTION_ASYNCHRONOUS. This option adds the restriction that the



4301 *   this S-function and the destination function-call subsystem cannot reside



4302 *   in conditionally executed subsystems. This option should be used when the



4303 *   destination function-call subsystem is going to be directly attached to an



4304 *   interrupt. This added restriction is useful to prevent conceptual modeling



4305 *   errors. Specifically, if an function-call subsystem resides within an



4306 *   enabled subsystem, you would assume that it will only execute occur when



4307 *   the enable signal is > 0, but this would not be the behavior if the



4308 *   function-call subsystem were to be attached to an interrupt. Therefore



4309 *   this option prevents this possible source of confusion.



4310 *   Note, during simulation (and not code generation), Simulink allows the



4311 *   S-function to reside in a conditionally executed subsystem. See the



4312 *   VxWorks interrupt block for an example - in simulation we use a



4313 *   triggered subsystem to simulate the interrupt and during code generation



4314 *   the trigger port is removed.



4315 *



4316 *



4317 * SS_OPTION_ASYNCHRONOUS_CUSTOM - Similar to SS_OPTION_ASYNCHRONOUS, except



4318 *   items 3a, 3b are removed.



4319 *



4320 * SS_OPTION_ASYNC_RATE_TRANSITION - Use this when your s-function converts a



4321 *   guarantees data integrity when transferring data to/from an



4322 *   asynchronously executed function-call subsystem. There are two types



4323 *   of data transfers: periodic to asynchronous task transitions or



4324 *   asynchronous to asynchronous task transitions. An asynchronously executed



4325 *   function-call subsystem is a function-call subsystem driven by an



4326 *   S-function with the SS_OPTION_ASYNCHRONOUS specified.



4327 *



4328 *   Within Simulink, two classes of 'asynchronous rate transitions' are



4329 *   defined:



4330 *   1) Read-write pairs. In this scenario, two blocks (using a technique



4331 *      such as double buffering) ensure data integrity in a multitasking



4332 *      environment. When creating the read-write pair of blocks, the



4333 *      S-functions for these blocks should set SS_OPTION_ASYNC_RATE_TRANSITION.



4334 *      Furthermore, the Mask Type for the read block, must include



4335 *      the string 'read' and the write block must include the string 'write'.



4336 *      For example, in the VxWorks library, we have the



4337 *        Asynchronous Rate Transition (Reader)



4338 *        Asynchronous Rate Transition (Writer)



4339 *      pairs.



4340 *   2) A single (protected or unprotected) block such as the



4341 *      VxWorks, Unprotected Asynchronous Rate Transition block.



4342 *      To create a single Protected Rate Transition block, you



4343 *      need to create a block like:



4344 *        +-------------------+



4345 *        |     +-------+     |



4346 *        | O-->| S-fcn |-->O |--->



4347 *        |     +-------+     |



4348 *        +-------------------+



4349 *      where the outport has a Tag value set to AsyncRateTransition



4350 *      and the S-function provides the code for the protected



4351 *      transition. Note, this S-function should not set the



4352 *      SS_OPTION_ASYNC_RATE_TRANSITION.



4353 *



4354 *



4355 * SS_OPTION_RATE_TRANSITION - Use this while your S-function is behaving



4356 *   as a unit delay or ZOH. This option is only supported for these two



4357 *   operations. A unit delay operation is identified by the presence



4358 *   of mdlUpdate and if not present then the operation is ZOH.



4359 *



4360 * SS_OPTION_NONSTANDARD_PORT_WIDTHS - If your S-function has mdl



4361 *   set input/output port routines with dynamically sized ports and the port



4362 *   widths don't follow the standard rules of scalar expansion or



4363 *   vector collapsing, then you may need to set this flag for Simulink.



4364 *   This usually occurs when the output width is not 1 and not equal to the



4365 *   maximum of the input widths.



4366 *



4367 * SS_OPTION_PORT_SAMPLE_TIMES_ASSIGNED - Use this when you have



4368 *   registered multiple sample times (ssSetNumSampleTimes > 1) to



4369 *   specify the rate at when each input and output port is running at.



4370 *   The simulation engine needs this information when checking for



4371 *   illegal rate transitions.



4372 *



4373 * SS_OPTION_SFUNCTION_INLINED_FOR_RTW - Set this if you have a .tlc file



4374 *   for your S-function and do not have a mdlRTW method. Setting option



4375 *   has no effect if you have a mdlRTW method. This option is like an



4376 *   assertion. During code generation, if this option is set and



4377 *   Real-Time Workshop cannot locate the TLC-file for the S-function,



4378 *   Real-Time Workshop will generate and error. If this option is not present



4379 *   and Real-Time Workshop locates a TLC-file for the S-function, it will be



4380 *   used.



4381 *



4382 * SS_OPTION_ALLOW_PARTIAL_DIMENSIONS_CALL - Use this if the block can



4383 *   handle partially known dimensions in the mdlSetInputPortDimensionInfo



4384 *   or mdlSetOutputPortDimensionInfo methods.  By default, Simulink



4385 *   calls mdlSetInput(Output)PortDimensionInfo methods, if the



4386 *   candidate port dimensions are fully known. That is, when the number of



4387 *   dimensions and dimensions are known. If this flag is set, Simulink may



4388 *   call mdlSetInput(Output)PortDimensionInfo with partial dimension



4389 *   information.  As an example, the methods may be called when the port



4390 *   width is known, but the actual dimensions are unknown.



4391 *



4392 *



4393 * SS_OPTION_ADA_S_FUNCTION - Used to interface with Ada Coded S-functions.



4394 *   Not relevant for C-Mex S-Functions.



4395 *



4396 * SS_OPTION_FORCE_NONINLINED_FCNCALL - Use this flag if the block requires



4397 *   that all function-call subsystems that it calls should be generated as



4398 *   procedures instead of possibly being generated as inlined code.



4399 *



4400 * SS_OPTION_USE_TLC_WITH_ACCELERATOR -  Use this to force the Accelerator



4401 *   to use the TLC inlining code for a S-function which will speed up



4402 *   execution of the S-function.  By default, the Accelerator will use



4403 *   the mex version of the S-function even though a TLC file for the



4404 *   S-function exists. This option should not be set for device driver



4405 *   blocks (A/D) or when there is an incompatibility between running the



4406 *   mex Start/InitializeConditions functions together with the TLC



4407 *   Outputs/Update/Derivatives.



4408 *



4409 * SS_OPTION_SIM_VIEWING_DEVICE - This s-function is a SimViewingDevice.  As



4410 *   long as it meets the other requirement for this type of block (no states,



4411 *   no outputs, etc), it will be considered to be an external mode block



4412 *   (show up in the external mode gui and no code is generated for it).



4413 *   During an external mode simulation, this block is run on the host only.



4414 *



4415 * SS_OPTION_SIM_INPUT_DEVICE - Mark this s-function as a SimInputDevice.  When



4416 *   this option is set and this s-function registered an mdlExtModeExec fcn,



4417 *   then it will be run in external mode.



4418 *



4419 * SS_OPTION_CALL_TERMINATE_ON_EXIT - Use this to force a call to mdlTerminate



4420 *   when (a) the S-function block has finished mdlWorkWidths, or (b) the



4421 *   S-function block is being destroyed.



4422 *



4423 * SS_OPTION_REQ_INPUT_SAMPLE_TIME_MATCH - Use this to option to specify



4424 *   that the input signal sample time(s) match the sample time assigned



4425 *   to the block input port. For example:



4426 *



4427 *      .-----------.           .---------------------------.



4428 *      |  src (.1) |---------->|  port based Ts S-fcn with |



4429 *      `-----------'           |  input Ts = 1             |



4430 *                              `---------------------------'



4431 *



4432 *   will generate an error if this option is set. If the block (or input port)



4433 *   sample time is inherited, then there will be no error generated.



4434 *



4435 * SS_OPTION_NONVOLATILE - Use this option to specify whether this s-function



4436 *   has side effects.  Set this option to request that Simulink remove



4437 *   this block if it is not needed (dead code).



4438 *



4439 * SS_OPTION_CAN_BE_CALLED_CONDITIONALLY - Use this option if the s-function



4440 *   can be called conditionally by other blocks.



4441 *



4442 * SS_OPTION_ALLOW_PORT_SAMPLE_TIME_IN_TRIGSS - Use this to specify that



4443 *   your port based sample time S-Function can handle being placed in a



4444 *   triggered like subsystem (e.g. triggered, function call, for, while).



4445 *   During sample time propagation use the macro ssSampleAndOffsetAreTriggered



4446 *   to determine if the sample and offset times correspond to the block



4447 *   being in a triggered subsystem. If the block is triggered, all port



4448 *   sample times must be either triggered or constant.



4449 *



4450 * SS_OPTION_ALLOW_CONSTANT_PORT_SAMPLE_TIME - Use this option to specify



4451 *   that your port-based sample time S-Function can handle constant sample



4452 *   times. This option is required whether the S-Function is going to



4453 *   originate the constant sample time or can have one propagated to it.



4454 *



4455 * SS_OPTION_WORKS_WITH_CODE_REUSE - Use this option to specify that your



4456 *   S-Function will work in a system that is being reused in RTW



4457 *   generated code.  If this option is not set, then the system that



4458 *   this S-Function lives in will not be reused.



4459 *



4460 * SS_OPTION_SUPPORTS_ALIAS_DATA_TYPES - This is used to state whether



4461 *   or not this block supports alias data types



4462 *



4463 * SS_OPTION_NO_INFLUENCE_ON_DEFAULT_MDL_DIMS - When dimensions propagation



4464 * to converge to a set of dimensions, blocks are queried individually



4465 * to setup their default dimensions. In the case of the S-function, this is



4466 * done by calling the mdlSetDefaultPortDimensions function. If the S-function



4467 * has no clear means of identifying a default set of dimensions, please



4468 * use this flag to postpone calls to mdlSetDefaultPortDimensions.



4469 */



4470#if SS_SFCN_LEVEL_1 || !SS_SFCN

4472#endif

4655# define _ssCacheSFcnParamValueAttribs(pName, dtId, nDims, dimsPtr, cplx) \



4656     ssParamRec locPI; \



4657     locPI.name             = pName; \



4658     locPI.nDimensions      = nDims; \



4659     locPI.dimensions       = dimsPtr; \



4660     locPI.complexSignal    = cplx; \



4661     locPI.dataTypeId       = dtId; \



4662     locPI.data             = NULL; \



4663     locPI.dataAttributes   = NULL; \



4664     locPI.nDlgParamIndices = 0; \



4665     locPI.dlgParamIndices  = NULL; \



4666     locPI.transformed      = RTPARAM_NOT_TRANSFORMED; \



4667     locPI.outputAsMatrix   = false;



4668



4669#define ssCheckSFcnParamValueAttribs(S,pIdx,pName,dtId,nDims,dimsPtr,cplx) \



4670   { \



4671      _ssCacheSFcnParamValueAttribs(pName, dtId, nDims, dimsPtr, cplx) \



4672      if (!_ssSafelyCallGenericFcnStart(S)(S, \



4673GEN_FCN_CHECK_SFCN_PARAM_VALUE_ATTRIBS, pIdx, &locPI) \



4674      _ssSafelyCallGenericFcnEnd) return; \



4675   }

5188/*======================================================================*



5189 * BUS support for S-Functions



5190 *======================================================================*/



5191



5192/*



5193 * APIS for bus support via bus expansion. In this case,



5194 * the s-function block is expanded under the hood into an individual



5195 * s-function for each signal in the bus and then the outputs re-bused



5196 * to output a bus.



5197 *



5198 * Need to set_param(gcb, 'EnableBusSupport', 'on') for the S-Function block



5199 *



5200 * 1) ssSetBusPropagationSupported(S, true)



5201 *    This indicates that bus expansion is desired.



5202 *



5203 * 2) ssSetBusSourcePort(S, portNumber)



5204 *    This indicates that the bus coming into port number (0-based) of the



5205 *    block will supply the structure of the outgoing bus. This bus is also



5206 *    used for getting signal names, signal propagation etc. It is the



5207 *    defining bus for this block.



5208 *    Example: Say for the switch block, this would be set to 0.



5209 *



5210 * 3) ssSetBusInputPorts(S, int number, int* numbers)



5211 *    This indicates the ports of the blocks that accept buses. The bus



5212 *    expansion routine then checks to verify that the incoming buses at these



5213 *    inports are identical in terms of signal names and compiled attributes



5214 *    for successful expansion.



5215 *    Example: For the switch block this is [0 2], so "number" is set to 2



5216 *             and "numbers" is an array of ints of length 2 with values



5217 *             numbers[0] = 0; numbers[1] = 2;



5218 */



5219#define ssSetBusPropagationSupported(S, value)\



5220{    boolean_T tmp = value;\



5221 _ssSafelyCallGenericFcnStart(S)((S),GEN_FCN_SET_BUS_PROPAGATION, 0, &tmp)\



5222 _ssSafelyCallGenericFcnEnd;\



5223}



5224



5225#define ssSetBusSourcePort(S, port)\



5226{    int tmp = port;\



5227 _ssSafelyCallGenericFcnStart(S)((S),GEN_FCN_SET_BUS_SOURCE_PORT, 0, &tmp)\



5228 _ssSafelyCallGenericFcnEnd;\



5229}



5230



5231#define ssSetBusInputPorts(S, numInports, value)\



5232 _ssSafelyCallGenericFcnStart(S)((S),GEN_FCN_SET_BUS_INPORTS, numInports, value)\



5233 _ssSafelyCallGenericFcnEnd



5234



5235/*



5236 * APIS for bus support via bus objects. In this case, the s-function outputs



5237 * a bus as defined by a bus object (which can be a parameter). The output



5238 * function should implement the bus output consistent with the bus object.



5239 *



5240 * Need to set_param(gcb, 'EnableBusSupport', 'on') for the S-Function block



5241 *



5242 * 1)  ssSetBusOutputObjectName(S, int_T portNumber, char* busName)



5243 *     This specifies the bus object that defines the bus coming out of the



5244 *     s-function block at output number (0-based) of the block.



5245 *



5246 * 2)  ssSetBusInputAsStruct(S, int_T portNumber, boolean_T val)



5247 *     This specifies if the input bus as specified by the bus object should



5248 *     be converted to non-virtual if necessary. By setting it to true, an auto-



5249 *     conversion block is inserted behind the scenes to convert a virtual



5250 *     bus input to a non-virtual bus



5251 *



5252 * 3)  ssSetBusOutputAsStruct(S, int_T portNumber, boolean_T val)



5253 *     This specifies if the output bus as specified by the bus object should



5254 *     emerge as a structure (non-virtual) or a virtual bus. By setting it to false,



5255 *     a Signal Conversion block is automatically inserted behind the scenes to



5256 *     output a virtual bus.



5257 *



5258 *     --------------------------------------------------------------------------



5259 *     The next set of macros can be used to obtain information for a specific element



5260 *     of a bus object given the data type index of the bus object and the appropriate



5261 *     bus element index within the bus object. The data type index of the bus object



5262 *     is the index returned by Simulink when the bus object was registered in



5263 *     mdlInitializeSizes() (using ssRegisterTypeFromParameter() for example)



5264 *     --------------------------------------------------------------------------



5265 *



5266 * 4)  ssGetNumBusElements(S, int_T busTypeID)



5267 *     Get the number of bus elements in the specified bus object. The bus data type



5268 *     is passed in as the second argument.



5269 *



5270 * 5)  ssGetBusElementOffset(S, int_T busTypeID, int_T elemIdx)



5271 *     Obtain the offset in bytes (int_T) from the start of the bus data type to



5272 *     the specified bus element. The bus data type is passed in as the second



5273 *     argument and the bus element index (zero based index) is passed in as the



5274 *     third argument.



5275 *



5276 * 6)  ssGetBusElementDataType(S, int_T busTypeID, int_T elemIdx)



5277 *     Obtain the data type index (int_T) for the specified bus element. The bus data



5278 *     type is passed in as the second argument and the bus element index (zero based



5279 *     index) is passed in as the third argument.



5280 *



5281 * 7)  ssGetBusElementComplexSignal(S, int_T busTypeID, int_T elemIdx)



5282 *     Obtain the complexity (CSignal_T) of the specified bus element. The bus



5283 *     data type is passed in as the second argument and the bus element index (zero



5284 *     based index) is passed in as the third argument.



5285 *



5286 * 8)  ssGetBusElementNumDimensions(S, int_T busTypeID, int_T elemIdx)



5287 *     Obtain the number of signal dimensions (int_T) for the specified bus element.



5288 *     The bus data type is passed in as the second argument and the bus element index



5289 *     (zero based index) is passed in as the third argument.



5290 *



5291 * 9)  ssGetBusElementDimensions(S, int_T busTypeID, int_T elemIdx)



5292 *     Obtain the dimensions (const int_T*) for the specified bus element. Use in combination



5293 *     with ssGetBusElementNumDimensions() above to iterate over the integer array



5294 *     returned by this macro. The bus data type is passed in as the second argument



5295 *     and the bus element index (zero based index) is passed in as the third argument.



5296 *



5297 * 10) ssGetBusElementDimensionsMode(S, int_T busTypeID, int_T elemIdx)



5298 *     Obtain the dimensions mode (DimensionsMode_T) for the specified bus element.



5299 *     The bus data type is passed in as the second argument and the bus element index



5300 *     (zero based index) is passed in as the third argument.



5301 *



5302 * 11) ssGetBusElementName(S, int_T busTypeId, int_T elemIdx)



5303 *     Get the name (const char*) of the specified bus element. The bus data type is passed



5304 *     in as the second argument and the bus element index (zero based index) is



5305 *     passed in as the third argument.



5306 *



5307 * 12) ssIsDataTypeABus(S, int_T typeID)



5308 *     Determine if the data type ID passed in is a bus signal. A Boolean_T value is



5309 *     returned.



5310 *



5311 * 13) ssGetBusElementMin(S, int_T busTypeID, int_T elemIdx)



5312 *     Obtain the minimum (real_T) for the specified bus element.



5313 *     The bus data type is passed in as the second argument and the bus element index



5314 *     (zero based index) is passed in as the third argument.



5315 *



5316 * 14) ssGetBusElementMax(S, int_T busTypeID, int_T elemIdx)



5317 *     Obtain the maximum (real_T) for the specified bus element.



5318 *     The bus data type is passed in as the second argument and the bus element index



5319 *     (zero based index) is passed in as the third argument.



5320 */



5321

7514/*

7516 * issues warning for changes which are not notified to ODE/DAE solver via



7517 * ssSetSolverNeedsReset. Continuous states changes without solver resets are



7518 * unsafe and may be ignored in future releases. This check can be skipped for



7519 * efficiency if S-function is written correctly to reset the solver for all



7520 * state changes by using ssSetSkipContStatesConsistencyCheck(S,1)



7521 */

7726/* SupportRunTimeModelAPI - Runtime model API refers to the model function with



7727'outputs', 'derivs' and 'update' command. If the S-function block writes to



7728any persistent memory during mdlOutputs function, e.g., either dWork or a



7729persistent variable, it is likely that these block may need to set this



7730flag to false.



7731



7732Similarly, if the S-function block writes to any persistent memory other than dX



7733in the mdlDerivatives, or if the S-function block writes to any persistent memory



7734other than the discrete states in mdlUpdate, it is likely that this flag needs



7735to be set to false.



7736



7737The default value for the flag is true.



7738 */



7739#define ssSetSupportRunTimeModelAPI(S, arg)\



7740{\



7741    _ssSafelyCallGenericFcnStart(S)((S), GEN_FCN_SET_SUPPORT_RUNTIME_MODEL_API,arg, NULL)\



7742        _ssSafelyCallGenericFcnEnd;\



7743}

10741typedef struct {



10742    void* data;



10743    int_T dtId;



10744    int8_T* result;



10745} DataQueryInfo;



10746



10747#define _ssIsPositiveDataValue(S, inData, inDtId, inResult)                    \



10748    {                                                                          \



10749        DataQueryInfo info;                                                    \



10750        info.data = (inData);                                                  \



10751        info.dtId = (inDtId);                                                  \



10752        info.result = (inResult);                                              \



10753        _ssSafelyCallGenericFcnStart(S)(S, GEN_FCN_IS_POSITIVE_DATA_VALUE, 0,  \



10754                                        &info) _ssSafelyCallGenericFcnEnd;     \



10755    }



10756



10757#define _ssSignDataValue(S, inData, inDtId, inResult)                          \



10758    {                                                                          \



10759        DataQueryInfo info;                                                    \



10760        info.data = (inData);                                                  \



10761        info.dtId = (inDtId);                                                  \



10762        info.result = (inResult);                                              \



10763        _ssSafelyCallGenericFcnStart(S)(S, GEN_FCN_SIGN_DATA_VALUE, 0, &info)  \



10764            _ssSafelyCallGenericFcnEnd;                                        \



10765    }

11025/*



11026 * ssCallSystemWithTID -



11027 *  This is used by S-function blocks to execute a function-call subsystem



11028 *  which are attached to the first output port of your S-function block.



11029 *  For blocks with multiple output ports, all "function-call's" must



11030 *  be performed on the first output port.



11031 */



11032#if SS_RT



11033#ifdef __cplusplus



11034extern "C" {



11035#endif



11036    extern int_T rt_CallSys(SimStruct *S, int_T element, int_T tid);



11037#ifdef __cplusplus



11038}



11039#endif



11040# define ssCallSystemWithTid(S,element,tid)          \



11041    (((S)->callSys.fcns[(element)] != NULL) ?        \



11042     rt_CallSys((S),(element),(tid)):1)



11043#ifdef __cplusplus



11044extern "C" {



11045#endif



11046    extern int_T rt_EnableSys(SimStruct *S, int_T element, int_T tid);



11047#ifdef __cplusplus



11048}



11049#endif



11050# define ssEnableSystemWithTid(S,element,tid)                           \



11051    (((S)->callSys.fcns[ssGetOutputPortWidth((S),0)+(element)] != NULL || \



11052      (S)->callSys.fcns[2*ssGetOutputPortWidth((S),0)+(element)] != NULL) ? \



11053     rt_EnableSys((S),(element),(tid)):1)



11054#ifdef __cplusplus



11055extern "C" {



11056#endif



11057    extern int_T rt_DisableSys(SimStruct *S, int_T element, int_T tid);



11058#ifdef __cplusplus



11059}



11060#endif



11061# define ssDisableSystemWithTid(S,element,tid)                          \



11062    (((S)->callSys.fcns[3*ssGetOutputPortWidth((S),0)+(element)] != NULL) ? \



11063     rt_DisableSys((S),(element),(tid)):1)



11064#else /* #if SS_RT */



11065# define ssCallSystemWithTid(S,element,tid)   \



11066    (((S)->callSys.fcns[(element)] != NULL) ? \



11067     ((*(S)->callSys.fcns[(element)])         \



11068      ((S)->callSys.args1[(element)],                   \



11069       (S)->callSys.args2[(element)], (tid)) ?          \



11070      (ssGetErrorStatus(S) == NULL) : (0)) : (1))



11071



11072#if defined(RSIM_WITH_SL_SOLVER)



11073# define ssEnableSystemWithTid(S,element,tid)                           \



11074    ((((S)->callSys.fcns[ssGetOutputPortWidth((S),0)+(element)] != NULL) ? \



11075      ((*(S)->callSys.fcns[ssGetOutputPortWidth((S),0)+(element)]) (    \



11076          (S)->callSys.args1[(element)],                                \



11077          (S)->callSys.args2[(element)], (tid)) ?                       \



11078       (ssGetErrorStatus(S) == NULL) : (0)) : (1)) &                    \



11079     (((S)->callSys.fcns[2*ssGetOutputPortWidth((S),0)+(element)] != NULL) ? \



11080      ((*(S)->callSys.fcns[2*ssGetOutputPortWidth((S),0)+(element)]) (  \



11081          (S)->callSys.args1[(element)],                                \



11082          (S)->callSys.args2[(element)], (tid)) ?                       \



11083       (ssGetErrorStatus(S) == NULL) : (0))  : (1)))



11084



11085# define ssDisableSystemWithTid(S,element,tid)                          \



11086    (((S)->callSys.fcns[3*ssGetOutputPortWidth((S),0)+(element)] != NULL) ? \



11087     ((*(S)->callSys.fcns[3*ssGetOutputPortWidth((S),0)+(element)]) (   \



11088         (S)->callSys.args1[(element)],                                 \



11089         (S)->callSys.args2[(element)], (tid)) ?                        \



11090      (ssGetErrorStatus(S) == NULL) : (0))  : (1))



11091#else /* #if defined(RSIM_WITH_SL_SOLVER) */



11092# define ssEnableSystemWithTid(S,element,tid)                           \



11093    (((S)->callSys.fcns[ssGetOutputPortWidth((S),0)+(element)] != NULL) ? \



11094     ((*(S)->callSys.fcns[ssGetOutputPortWidth((S),0)+(element)]) (     \



11095         (S)->callSys.args1[(element)],                                 \



11096         (S)->callSys.args2[(element)], (tid)) ?                        \



11097      (ssGetErrorStatus(S) == NULL) : (0))  : (1))



11098



11099# define ssDisableSystemWithTid(S,element,tid)                          \



11100    (((S)->callSys.fcns[2*ssGetOutputPortWidth((S),0)+(element)] != NULL) ? \



11101     ((*(S)->callSys.fcns[2*ssGetOutputPortWidth((S),0)+(element)]) (   \



11102         (S)->callSys.args1[(element)],                                 \



11103         (S)->callSys.args2[(element)], (tid)) ?                        \



11104      (ssGetErrorStatus(S) == NULL) : (0))  : (1))



11105#endif /* #if defined(RSIM_WITH_SL_SOLVER) */

11475/*  ssCallConvertBuiltInDType



11476 *  Options:



11477 *      satOnIntOverFlow:



11478 *          If true, saturate.  If false, the conversion is undefined when



11479 *          values are out of range (platform dependent conversion).



11480 *      doDiff:



11481 *          If true, compare original values and converted values and return



11482 *          true if they are different (e.g., value was saturated, etc).  If



11483 *          doDiff is false, this function always returns true.



11484 */



11485#if SS_SIM



11486#define ssCallConvertBuiltInDType(S,nVals,satOnIntOverFlow,doDiff,dt1,v1,dt2,v2)  \



11487    (S)->states.modelMethods2->ConvertBuiltInDType(nVals,satOnIntOverFlow,doDiff, \



11488        dt1,v1,dt2,v2)



11489#else



11490# define ssCallConvertBuiltInDType(S,nVals,satOnIntOverFlow,doDiff,dt1,v1,dt2,v2)  \



11491    ssCallConvertBuiltInDType_cannot_be_used_in_RTW



11492#endif

11887#define ssIsTIDInStInfo(S,tid) \



11888        (((tid) >= 0) && \



11889         ((tid) < (ssGetParentSS(S) ? \



11890                   ssGetNumSampleTimes(ssGetParentSS(S)) : \



11891                   ssGetNumSampleTimes(S))) && \



11892         (ssGetSampleTimeTaskID(S,tid) < ssGetNumRootSampleTimes(S)))

12548/*------------------------- ssIsContinuousTask ------------------------------*/



12549



12550#if SS_SL_INTERNAL || SS_SFCN_FOR_SIM



12551#if defined(RSIM_WITH_SOLVER_MULTITASKING) && RSIM_WITH_SOLVER_MULTITASKING



12552#if SS_TID01EQ_EQUAL_ONE



12553#define ssIsContinuousTask(S, tid) \



12554           ((tid) <= 1)



12555#else



12556# define ssIsContinuousTask(S,tid) \



12557           ((tid) == 0)



12558#endif



12559#else



12560 /*



12561  * During simulation, tid passed to S-functions is always 0 even in



12562  * multitasking mode



12563  */



12564# define ssIsContinuousTask(S,tid) (((tid) == 0) && (S)->mdlInfo->sampleHits[0])



12565#endif



12566#elif SS_TID01EQ_EQUAL_ONE



12567#define ssIsContinuousTask(S, tid) \



12568           ((tid) <= 1)



12569#else



12570# define ssIsContinuousTask(S,tid) \



12571           ((tid) == 0)



12572#endif



12573



12574#define ssIsAsyncTID(S,sti) \



12575           (ssGetSampleTimeTaskID(S,sti) >= \



12576            ssGetNumRootSampleTimes(S))



12577



12578/*-------------------------- ssIsSampleHit ----------------------------------*/



12579#if SS_MULTITASKING || (defined(RSIM_WITH_SOLVER_MULTITASKING) && RSIM_WITH_SOLVER_MULTITASKING)



12580



12581#define ssIsSampleHit(S,sti,tid) \



12582            (!ssIsTIDInStInfo(S,sti) || \



12583            (ssGetSampleTimeTaskID(S,sti) == (tid)))



12584



12585#else



12586



12587# define ssIsSampleHit(S,sti,tid) \



12588            (((tid) != CONSTANT_TID) && \



12589             (!ssIsTIDInStInfo(S,sti) || \



12590             (ssIsMajorTimeStep(S) && \



12591              (ssGetSampleHitPtr(S))[ssGetSampleTimeTaskID(S,sti)])))



12592



12593#endif



12594



12595/*------------------------- ssSetSampleHitInTask ----------------------------*/



12596#if SS_MULTITASKING || SS_SL_INTERNAL || SS_SFCN_FOR_SIM



12597# define _ssSetSampleHitInTask(S, task_j, task_i, hit) \



12598            (S)->mdlInfo->perTaskSampleHits[(task_j) + \



12599              ((task_i) * (ssGetNumSampleTimes(S)))] = (hit)



12600# if !SS_SFCN



12601# define ssSetSampleHitInTask(S, task_j, task_i, hit) \



12602           _ssSetSampleHitInTask(S, task_j, task_i, hit)



12603# else



12604#define ssSetSampleHitInTask(S, task_j, task_i, hit) \



12605           ssSetSampleHitInTask_cannot_be_used_in_SFunctions



12606# endif



12607#endif



12608



12609/*----------------------- ssIsSpecialSampleHit ------------------------------*/



12610



12611#if SS_MULTITASKING || SS_SL_INTERNAL || SS_SFCN_FOR_SIM



12612/*



12613 * The ssIsSpecialSampleHit(S, my_sti, promoted_sti, tid) macro will be



12614 * "true" if the block is executing in a major time step in context of a



12615 * promoted sample time (promoted_sti) and we have a sample hit in the



12616 * original task (my_sti) which translates to:



12617 *    1) tid == tid_for(promoted_sti). It is required that this macro be



12618 *       invoked with in a ssIsSampleHit(S,promoted_sti,tid) to guarantee this



12619 *       case.



12620 *    2) Must be major time step.



12621 *    3) my_sti (the block's sti) has a sample hit at the current point in



12622 *       time.



12623 * Valid usage in an S-function would be:



12624 *	if (ssIsSampleHit(S, promoted_sti)) {



12625 *        if (ssIsSpecialSampleHit(S, my_sti, promoted_sti, tid)) {



12626 *        }



12627 *      }



12628 * providing promoted_sti is not the continuous task. If promoted_sti is



12629 * the continuous task, then the following must be used:



12630 *	if (ssIsContinuousTask(S, promoted_sti)) {



12631 *        if (ssIsSpecialSampleHit(S, my_sti, promoted_sti, tid)) {



12632 *        }



12633 *      }



12634 *



12635 * Note, failure to wrap ssIsSpecialSampleHit() within ssIsSampleHit() or



12636 * ssIsContinuousTask will result in unexpected behavior.



12637 */



12638#define ssIsSampleHitInTask(S, my_sti, tid) \



12639            (ssGetPerTaskSampleHitsPtr(S))[ \



12640              ssGetSampleTimeTaskID(S,my_sti) + \



12641                ((tid) * (ssGetNumRootSampleTimes(S)))]



12642



12643#  define ssIsSpecialSampleHit(S, my_sti, promoted_sti, tid) \



12644            (ssIsMajorTimeStep(S) && ssIsSampleHitInTask(S, my_sti, \



12645             ssGetSampleTimeTaskID(S,promoted_sti)))



12646#else



12647#  define ssIsSpecialSampleHit(S, my_sti, promoted_sti, tid) \



12648            ssIsSampleHit(S, my_sti, tid)



12649#endif



12650



12651#define ssGetNumRootSampleTimes(S) ssGetNumSampleTimes(ssGetRootSS(S))



12652
